observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our last year’s recommendations and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

instruct the GSO to process all purchasing concerns and keep track of the movement of stocks on hand from receipt until issuance for accounting, control and accountability purposes;

consider in the budget preparation for the ensuing year, the provision of a storage room so that the procurement of supplies in significant quantities can be stored to lessen the administrative cost in frequent procurements and reimbursements;

instruct the GSO to (i) prepare and maintain stock cards for the purchased supplies; (ii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation; and (iii) procure, as far as practicable and feasible, directly from the PS-DBM all anticipated common-use supplies, and resort to local suppliers only upon unavailability of supplies needed; and

require the Municipal Accountant to (i) ensure that all purchase of supplies and materials are recorded under the proper inventory account; (ii) prepare supplies ledger cards for delivered items as called for in the above-quoted regulation.
We also recommended that the LCE instruct the (a) Municipal Accountant to ensure that the RIS and SSMI or equivalent documents were attached to the vouchers prior to the recording of expenditures in the appropriate accounts; (b) Municipal Accountant and GSO to reconcile and investigate the discrepancies in their respective records and the results of the physical count conducted; and (c) end-users to submit the lacking document/s noted in the Annex “C”.

We reiterate and supplement our previous year’s recommendations and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive require the BAC, BAC Secretariat and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of RA 9184, its IRR and relevant rules and regulations in the Municipality’s procurement process by:

paying attention on the procurement lapses noted above specifically under items 7.8. and 7.46, to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements;

attending the mandatory training on procurement and regularly checking for updates on procurement and, if possible, attending seminars on latest issuances pertaining to procurement and other relevant rules and regulations at least once a year, or as needed, as prescribed under the revised IRR of RA 9184 to keep abreast with the latest issuances and be able to comply with the prescribed requirements accordingly;

furnishing the COA with copies of all purchase orders/contracts and all papers relative thereto within five (5) days after the perfection of the contract and sending of notification of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries to the Office of the Auditor pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2009-001 and 95-006;

proving the non-duplication of works in reference to payments made for the same project as mentioned in item 7.18 hereof, otherwise refund the amount;

submitting the lacking documents of the projects mentioned in Annex E, for further evaluation as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action; and

for future similar undertakings on infrastructure projects, (i) conducting complete detailed engineering prior to the preparation of bid documents in order to assure the viability of infrastructure projects; (ii) complying with the requirements in preparing the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) specifically defined under DPWH Department Order No. 197, series 2016; and (iii) conducting materials and items of work testing by the Municipal Engineer or the Project Engineer.

We also recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

direct the GAD Focal Point Person to coordinate efforts with the Municipal Budget Officer to initiate the preparation of an adjusted GPB to match the available budget for the fund and augment PPAs that had incurred overspending during the year, if warranted;

provide justification on the noted ineligible charges to the fund specified under Item 12.13 of the memorandum;

take note of the ineligible charges to prevent recurrence in the future and utilize in full the total appropriated fund in accordance with the GPB approved by the DILG to ensure full attainment of the GAD targets/objectives;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the requirements on the preparation of Subsidiary Ledgers in consonance with COA Circular 2021-008; and

require the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to review the approved GAD Plan and Budget and allow those expenses that are directly related in the implementation of GAD PPAs. Avoid, as much as possible, allowing grants/financial assistance that do not directly address specific gender issues in the locality to be charged under the GAD Fund.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation and made additional recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:

direct the HRMO to (i) continue to look for possible candidates from the array of JO workers for permanency based on available vacant positions for recommendation to the Personnel Selection Board (PSB) to reduce the number of job orders, taking into consideration the mandated PS limitation under the Local Government Code; (ii) prepare and issue policy guidelines on hiring/recruitment; (iii) conduct spot checking/regular monitoring of personnel as to services rendered; (iv) assess the existing organizational structure so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established, avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job order personnel.

reduce the number of job orders in the Municipality by objectively conducting work evaluation along with the HRMO and immediate superiors of concerned JOs, to assess personnel who are value adding to the LGU;

relieve overaged personnel and strictly adhere to the policies and guidelines in the hiring of personnel under contract of services and job orders as provided for in CSC Memorandum No. 17, s. 2002, promulgating CSC Resolution No. 02-0790;

consider, if budget permits, the provision for an increase in pay of the existing JOs at par with comparable positions in the government; and

direct the Municipal Accountant to look into the noted deficiencies as mentioned in Item 13.22 of this Memorandum, before allowing payments thereof.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require officials concerned to:
instruct the Inventory Committee to (i) expedite the preparation of Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) as required by the Circular and if warranted, appoint additional IC members to fast track the cleansing of PPE records; and (ii) henceforth, conduct periodic inventory as required by the MNGAS to avoid the recurrence of discrepancies in the PPE records of the LGU;
require the Municipal Accountant to exert efforts to (i) prepare the Property, Plant, and Equipment Ledger Cards and Construction in Progress Ledger Card starting with the current year’s acquisition and eventually to prior years’ acquisitions and aim for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are all covered; (ii) reclassify the cited CY  2023 completed projects which were erroneously recorded as CIP to respective PPE accounts; and (iii) investigate the status of the projects from CY 2018-2022 currently recorded in the CIP accounts and effect the necessary entries based from the results of the investigation;
require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to (i) work coordinately with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer on the inventory of all local road projects with complete description and cost segregation of road components to ensure proper recording and control of the assets and prepare the respective Local Road Network Ledger Cards and Local Road Network Property Card; and (ii) cause the tracing of the initial recognition of all PPE to comply with the preparation and maintenance of Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards;
enjoin Accountant, GSO, and Municipal Engineer to attend training/s relative to LRAMM by the DILG, adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and comply with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the appropriate adjusting journal entries, if warranted, to correct the misstatements of the affected accounts. Henceforth, ensure that costs of major repairs, rehabilitation, improvement, and construction of infrastructure assets are capitalized or recognized as property, plant and equipment, in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) No. 17 and related rules on asset recognition; and (ii) recognize depreciation using a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year and asset impairment to reflect the accurate value of PPE in the financial statements.

We reiterated our last year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require officials concerned to:
instruct the GSO to (i) consolidate all purchase requests pertaining to the procurement of supplies and submit the consolidated request to the Bids and Awards Committee for centralized procurement to avail of the quantity discount inherent to bulk orders; and (ii) keep track of the movement of stocks on hand from receipt until issuance for accounting, control and accountability purposes;
consider in the budget preparation for the ensuing year, the provision of a storage room/central warehouse so that the procurement of supplies in significant quantities can be stored to take advantage of discounts inherent to bulk purchases and lessen the administrative cost associated with frequent procurements and reimbursements;
instruct the GSO and all concerned departments to (i) prepare and maintain stock cards for the recording of purchases and issuances; (ii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation; and (iii) consolidate the purchase requests of all departments and procure, as far as practicable and feasible, directly from the PS-DBM all requested common-use supplies and equipment, and resort to local suppliers only upon unavailability of supplies needed;
require the Municipal Accountant to (i) ensure that all purchase of supplies and materials are recorded under the proper inventory account; (ii) prepare supplies ledger cards for delivered items as called for in the above-quoted regulation; and ensure RIS and SSMI or equivalent documents were attached to the vouchers prior to the recording of expenditures in the appropriate accounts; and
Municipal Accountant and GSO to reconcile and investigate the discrepancies uncovered in their respective records against the physical count of inventories.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive to require the LDC, MPDO and MBO:
(a)    continue the checking/regular monitoring of the fund’s utilization in harmony with the approved AIP;
(b)    present in detail the PPAs charged under the 20% DF in the Annual Investment Program (AIP);
(c)    continuously refer to the JMC for appropriate guidance in crafting the Annual Investment Program and inclusion of PPAs on the 20% DF that will aim to fully attain the desired socio-economic development targets of the LGU;
(d)    ensure consistency in the adequacy of allocation and continued adherence with the mandated utilization of the fund in accordance with pertinent provisions of the JMC; and
(e)    seek approval from the SB of projects charged to the appropriation described in generic terms and henceforth, clearly specify the projects to be charged against the DF to dispense the need to secure such SB approval for the timely implementation of the development projects.
Furthermore, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
(a)    Municipal Engineer to (i) submit explanation on the observed inconsistencies of development projects; (ii) henceforth, strictly monitor the implementation of projects and see to it that approved plans and detailed engineering documents were observed; and (iii) if warranted under the circumstances, prepare variation order if deviation from the original plan is inevitable;
(b)    BAC Chairman to look into the noted deviations on the procurement of goods and infrastructure projects, to avert the recurrence thereof on future similar undertakings; and
(c)    direct the Municipal Accountant to facilitate the deduction of retention money that will serve as warranty from defects of procured goods and infrastructure projects; (ii) in coordination with the former BAC Chairperson, to cause the submission the noted deficient documents in item 1.25.1 of this Memorandum for further evaluation of the Audit Team; and (iii) henceforth, see to it the supporting documents of projects were complete prior to making payment/s.

We reiterated our last year’s audit recommendations and made additions thereto and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require officials concerned to:
the LDRRMO in coordination with the LDRRMC to (i) prepare and submit annually the LDRRMFIP for the DRRM program of the LGU in reference to COA Circular 2012-002 to cover for the available unexpended balance of prior years, if available; (ii) see to it that all plans and programs contained in the approved plan and budget for disaster are fully implemented during the year; (iii) regularly review the 3-year LDDRMF plan to address current vulnerabilities and account for changes, as warranted; and (iv) gradually comply with the minimum standards on disaster preparedness based on available resources;
the LDRRMO in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to (i) henceforth strictly monitor the sources and utilization of the LDRRMF by including not only the budget for the year and continuing appropriations but also other sources such as funds from NDRRMF, from other LGUs and other sources in the monthly report; and (ii) submit justification on the noted charges to the fund as provided in Item 5.24 this report, for evaluation of the Audit Team;
the Municipal Accountant to immediately facilitate the recording of the “Trust Liability-DRRM in the accounting records as at December 31, 2023;
the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Local Finance Committee facilitate the (i) actual transfer of unexpended LDRRMF in the special trust fund; and (iii) reversion of any unutilized LDRRMF held in trust after five years to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund as called for by the above-quoted Circular; and
direct the LDRRMO and MSWDO, to submit to (i) the GSO the issuance form for in-kind donations to facilitate the updating of registries of in-kind donations; and (ii) henceforward comply with the forms and reports provided under COA Circular 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation and made additions thereto and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
direct the Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the necessary subsidiary ledgers for all fund transfers for immediate tracking of the status of the fund at a given period; and (ii) continue to closely coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer as well as the Implementing Department to facilitate the immediate reconciliation of the outstanding fund transfers from various Source Agencies and return the unused funds from the results thereof, as warranted;
instruct the Local Finance Committee and the implementing departments to (i) review and submit the noted deficiencies in item 7.18.; and (ii) in case of   future similar undertaking, strictly adhere to the agreement or guidelines relative to the specific fund held in trust;
BAC to (i) henceforth, see to it that all of the required documents as required by GPPB, were substantially complied; and (ii) strictly observe the posting requirements as provided under the RIRR of the RA No. 9184 and Annex “H” thereof; and
in coordination with the implementing Department/s, (i) strictly adhere to the agreement or guidelines relative to the specific fund held in trust; (ii) duly notify the SA of any deviation/modifications from the approved project proposal and see to it that such modifications were duly approved prior to their implementation.

We reiterated and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
direct the GAD Focal Point System and the GAD Focal Point Person (i) to formulate the LGU’s GPB in accordance with the requirements of the JMC specifically on the endorsement required from DILG prior to the inclusion in the Annual Budget; (ii) communicate any changes to the GPB for the review and approval of the Provincial Government and the DILG; (iii) in coordination with MBO, MPDO and implementing departments to monitor the implementation of the GPB so that all of the GAD related PPAs are implemented during the year and introduce interventions to avoid delays in the implementation of GAD PPAs, if warranted; (iv) henceforth, submit the required approved GPB and GAD AR within the reglementary period; (v) review the noted lapses in item 8.24 of this report and avert recurrence thereof in the future to avoid further adverse audit action; and (vi) require to attend seminars and training to strengthen the mainstreaming of GAD in the LGU;
direct the MSWDO and other offices concerned to (i) strictly observe the provisions of the operations manual of the LGU in the granting of various assistance; and (ii) recommend revision thereof, through the help of the Sangguniang Bayan, to further improve the social services of the LGU, if warranted;
require the concerned personnel involved to provide justification on the noted ineligible charges to the fund specified under Item 8.23 of the report;
instruct the implementing departments of the LGU to henceforth, refrain from charging ineligible charges to the fund and utilize in full the total appropriated fund in accordance with the GPB approved by the DILG to ensure full attainment of the GAD targets/objectives; and
require the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to review the approved GAD Plan and Budget and allow those expenses that are directly related to the implementation of GAD PPAs. Avoid, as much as possible, allowing grants/financial assistance that do not directly address specific gender issues in the locality to be charged under the GAD Fund.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations and made additions thereto and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Designated MENRO:
to initiate the updating and fill-up required members of the SWMB in reference to Section 12 of the Act, to help in the SWM efforts of the LGU;
request the Barangays (i) to enhance/adapt the Municipal ordinances pertaining to solid waste cited above; (ii) without Materials Recovery Facility (MRF), to exert effort in locating appropriate MRF or, if possible, request other Barangays with MRF for the clustering scheme as allowed under the law;
continue to intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay, following the strategies identified under the approved 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU;
exercise strong political will to implement the applicable ordinances pertaining to Solid Waste Management and strengthen the implementation thereof at the Barangay level in order to achieve a community compliance and eventually abide by the necessities on preserving and protecting the environment required under the Act.
We also recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) check the noted deficiencies in item 9.35. to avert the recurrence thereof on future similar undertakings; and (ii) ensure the completeness of the documents submitted and exercise prudence in the checking before effecting payment.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to ensure that:
except for cash advances for training and travel, all special disbursing officers are formally designated and adequately bonded prior to the grant of the initial cash advance;
cash advances granted to Disbursing Officers and Special Disbursing Officers are within the limit of their cash accountability;
AOs comply with the required number of days within which to liquidate cash advances granted and the necessary supporting documents are attached to the liquidation reports;
the Municipal Accountant (i) checks the completeness of the supporting documents, signatories on liquidation reports; (ii) issues certification that the previous cash advance is liquidated/accounted for before the grant of another cash advance; and (iii) strictly monitors timely submission of liquidation reports and immediate refund of any unused balances and the timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
travelling expenses are given pursuant to EO 77 and lecturers/resource persons are paid in accordance with Budget Circular 2007-1; and
granting of CAs is limited to disbursements allowed by law and adhere closely to the requirements of the procurement law or RA 9184 and resort to cash advance only on meritorious cases.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
direct the HRMO to (i) continue to look for possible candidates from the array of JO workers for permanency based on available vacant positions for recommendation to the Personnel Selection Board (PSB) to reduce the number of job orders, taking into consideration the mandated PS limitation under the Local Government Code; (ii) prepare and issue policy guidelines on hiring/recruitment; (iii) conduct spot checking/regular monitoring of personnel as to services rendered; (iv) assess the existing organizational structure so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established, avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job order personnel;
reduce the number of job orders in the Municipality by objectively conducting work evaluation along with the HRMO and immediate superiors of concerned JOs, to assess personnel who are value adding to the LGU;
consider, if budget permits, the provision for an increase in pay of the existing JOs; and
direct the Municipal Accountant to look into the noted deficiencies as mentioned in Item 1.28 of this Memorandum, before allowing payments thereof.

We reiterated and supplemented our previous year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the BAC, BAC Secretariat and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of RA 9184, its IRR and relevant rules and regulations in the Municipality’s procurement process by:
paying attention on the procurement lapses noted above to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements;
furnishing the COA with copies of all purchase orders/contracts and all papers relative thereto within five (5) days after the perfection of the contract and sending of notification of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries to the Office of the Auditor pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2009-001 and 95-006;
in coordination with the Former BAC Chairman and Members submit the lacking documents of the projects mentioned in Annex A, for the immediate evaluation of the Audit Team; and
for future similar undertakings on infrastructure projects, (i) conducting complete detailed engineering prior to the preparation of bid documents in order to assure the viability of infrastructure projects; (ii) complying with the requirements in preparing the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) specifically defined under DPWH Department Order No. 197, series 2016; and (iii) conducting materials and items of work testing by the Municipal Engineer or the Project Engineer.
We also recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed:
in coordination with the previous BAC and BAC TWG (i) submit the deficient documents enumerated/identified in the discussions in Item 1.12 of this Memorandum; and (ii) submit detailed explanation or valid justification on observations cited in Item 16.27 of this report;
require the Punong Barangay of Barangay San Pablo Propio to submit explanation on the re-use of the metal parts of the partitions as these were intended for disaster preparation;
unless satisfactorily explained/validly justified or submitted proof of non-irregularities (i) refund the amount of ₱380,411.00 on the noted duplication of works; and (ii) request the contractor to refund ₱32,168.50 representing the item of work intended for the payment of CSHP;
instruct the BAC and BAC-TWG to give precedence in reviewing the noted deviations herein to avert similar observations on same undertakings in the future, otherwise continued failure to account for the inconsistencies noted above may warrant an administrative/criminal liability on the extent of the flagrant deviations of the law;
due to the recurring problems and deviations on procurement and purported irregularities review the current membership of the BAC to include capacitated and personnel with known integrity to process the procurement of the LGU, this is without prejudice to a criminal case that may be warranted for the inefficiencies noted overhead:
attend to mandatory and continuing training/s on procurement and regularly checking for updates on procurement in the GPPB website, to keep abreast with the latest issuances and be able to comply with prescribed requirements accordingly; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to check and ensure the completeness of the documents submitted and exercise prudence in the checking before effecting payment.

We reiterated and supplemented our previous recommendations and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

reconstitute an Inventory Committee, including at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Department of the LGU in pursuance to item 5.2. of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 who will spearhead the conduct of complete physical count of all the LGU’s properties, taking into account the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of PPEs;

require the General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to exert efforts to prepare the Property Cards and Property, Plant, and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aiming for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered;

require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to (i) work coordinately with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer on the inventory of all local road projects with complete description and cost segregation of road components to ensure proper recording and control of the assets and prepare the respective Local Road Network Ledger Cards and Local Road Network Property Card; and (ii) cause the tracing of the initial recognition of all PPE to comply with the preparation and maintenance of Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards;

enjoin Accountant, GSO, and Municipal Engineer to attend training/s relative to LRAMM by the DILG, adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and comply with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008; and

instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the appropriate adjusting journal entries, if warranted, to correct the misstatements of the affected accounts. Henceforth, ensure that costs of major repairs, rehabilitation, improvement, and construction of infrastructure assets are capitalized or recognized as property, plant and equipment, in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) No. 17 and related rules on asset recognition; and (ii) recognize depreciation using a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year and asset impairment to reflect the accurate value of PPE in the financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive ensure that:

except for cash advances for training and travel, all special disbursing officers are formally designated and adequately bonded prior to the grant of the initial cash advance;

cash advances granted to Disbursing Officers and Special Disbursing Officers are within the limit of their cash accountability;

AOs comply with the required number of days within which to liquidate cash advances granted and the necessary supporting documents are attached to the liquidation reports;

the Municipal Accountant (i) checks the completeness of the supporting documents, signatories on liquidation reports; (ii) issues certification that the previous cash advance is liquidated/accounted for before the grant of another cash advance; and (iii) strictly monitors timely submission of liquidation reports and immediate refund of any unused balances and the timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;

travelling expenses are given pursuant to EO 77 and lecturers/resource persons are paid in accordance with Budget Circular 2007-1;

submission of an exemption from the Comelec to support the disbursements for donations/assistance/allowance/subsidy granted during election ban;

granting of CAs is limited to disbursements allowed by law and adhere closely to the requirements of the procurement law or RA 9184 and resort to cash advance only on meritorious cases; and

on noted alterations, refund the difference in the amount of the original vis-a-vis the modification on official receipts.

We reiterated and also recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:

Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the necessary subsidiary ledgers for all fund transfers for immediate tracking of the status of the fund at a given period; (ii) continue to closely coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer as well as the Implementing Department to facilitate the immediate reconciliation of the outstanding fund transfers from various Source Agencies; and (iii) henceforth, furnish the GSO the necessary documents for the preparation of the PAR;

General Services Officer to include all the specific details of the procured Property, Plant and Equipment as well as the accessories attached thereto in the PAR to easily identify the property of the LGU and establish the accountability of the AO;

BAC to (i) henceforth, see to it that all of the required documents, such as but not limited to MOU as required by GPPB, were substantially complied prior to the conduct of EPA; and (ii) strictly observe the posting requirements and specified required time for each procurement activity as provided under the IRR of the RA No. 9184 and Annex “C” thereof; and

in coordination with the implementing Department/s, (i) strictly adhere to the agreement or guidelines relative to the specific fund held in trust; (ii) duly notify the SA of any deviation/modifications from the approved project proposal and see to it that such modifications were duly approved prior to their implementation; (iii) consider the distribution of the procured farm equipment to qualified farmers’ association/cooperative within the locality to address the limitations and increase the number of farmers that will benefit from the procured equipment; and (iv) submit explanation on the non-utilization of the procured mobile clinic.

We reiterated our prior years recommendations and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to request the concerned personnel to provide a certification signifying that charges under the fund are net of budgetary provisions provided by the DepEd and ECCD;

instruct the Local School Board and approving authorities of the expenditures to prepare a justification on the noted ineligible charges identified in item 9.11 and 9.13, otherwise, refund the amount glaringly ineligible as charges to the fund;

refrain from charging ineligible expenses to the fund and strictly adhere with the prioritized programs, projects and activities in reference to the above-mentioned rules and regulations; and

instruct Local School Board to submit a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to the schools giving emphasis on programs and projects that are deemed priority especially during these times of pandemic.

Henceforth, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) refrain from directly recording Donation account to record assistance and donations of material amount and require the submission of liquidation report upon exhaustion thereof to safeguard the SEF from possible theft and misappropriation; and (ii) noting the incomplete submission of liquidation documents, strictly check the documents submitted for liquidation prior to the derecognition of cash advances in the accounting books.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Local Chief Executive, thru the OIC-MENRO:

find a suitable location for the central MRF of the LGU and plan appropriate necessary actions such as inclusion of adequate funding to establish the same, among others;

carry on with the linkage already started with the Barangays of the Municipality in gaining support for the implementation of the ordinance specifically on the establishment of Barangay MRFs by recommending the clustering thereof as allowed by the Act and provide technical assistance on its establishment, if warranted;

intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay, following the strategies identified under the approved 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU and with focus on the volume reduction at source in cognizance with pertinent section as cited above:

exercise strong political will to implement the applicable ordinances pertaining to Solid Waste Management.

We also recommended that the LCE instruct the MENRO, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to survey the disposal facility for the necessary improvements needed to enhance the efficiency and safety of the temporary facility.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:
(a) require the BAC and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of RA 9184, its IRR and relevant rules and regulations in the Municipality’s procurement process by paying attention on the procurement lapses noted above, to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements such as, but not limited to the:

i. preparation of Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) as basis for the preparation of the Annual Procurement Plan (APP);

ii. furnishing COA with copies of all purchase orders/contracts and all papers relative thereto within five (5) days after the perfection of the contract and sending of notification of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries to the Office of the Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001 and 95-006;

iii. on future similar undertakings on infrastructure projects, conduct complete detailed engineering prior to the preparation of bid documents in order to assure the viability of infrastructure project;

iv. compliance with the requirements in preparing the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC), specifically defined under DPWH Department Order No. 197, series 2016; and

v. conduct of materials and items of work testing by the Municipal Engineer or the Project Engineer;

(b) require personnel involved in procurement and All BAC Members to regularly check for updates on procurement and if possible, attend webinars on latest issuances pertaining to procurement and other relevant rules and regulations at least once a year, or as needed, as prescribed under the revised implementing rules and regulations of RA 9184 to keep abreast with the latest issuances and be able to comply with prescribed requirements accordingly.

We also recommended that the LCE:
(a) in coordination with the BAC, (i) submit the lacking documents of the projects mentioned in Annex A, for further evaluation as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action; and (ii) prepare an explanation on other deficiencies noted also mentioned in Annex A; and
(b) necessitate the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:
(a) instruct concerned department heads to review the requirements and follow COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of PPEs and COA Circular No. 2015-008 in order to have a verifiable data on the existence, condition and accountability of the Municipality’s PPEs;
(b) reconstitute an Inventory Committee with adequate number of members, to include at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Department of the LGU in pursuance to item 5.2. of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020. To lead in the inventory-taking by office of all properties of the Municipality and to submit the Report of the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and property records;
(c) require the General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to exert efforts to prepare the Property Cards and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aim for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered;
(d) instruct the Municipal Engineer to conduct an initial inventory of an achievable percentage of local road networks and other infrastructure assets (by location) in the Municipality and record the same in the Books of Accounts as PPE in reference to the procedure set by COA Circular 2015-008; and
(e) require the Municipal Accountant to record in the books of accounts the unrecorded real properties and recognize depreciation using a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year and asset impairment to reflect the accurate value of PPE in the financial statements.

We further recommend to the Local Chief Executive enjoin all Department Heads concerned (Accountant, GSO, and Municipal Engineer) to attend trainings relative to LRAMM by the DILG, to be able to adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and eventual compliance with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008.

We restated our prior years recommendation that the Local Chief Executive instruct the concerned Municipal officials to:
(a) submit the lacking documents in compliance with item 13.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001, as stated in the Notice of Suspension dated January 3, 2022, for further evaluation and as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action; 
(b) submit written explanation on the noted deficiency in Item 1.4; 
(c) cause the proper titling of the purchased lots in the name of the Municipality as required by Section 23 (2), Chapter 4, Title 1-B, Book V, of the 1987 Administrative Code, and 
(d) on future similar undertakings, direct the Accountant to check the completeness of the supporting documents prior to payment as required under the above-quoted Circular.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive ensure that:
(a) except for cash advances for training and travel, all special disbursing officers are formally designated and adequately bonded prior to the grant of the initial cash advance;
(b) cash advances granted to Disbursing Officers and Special Disbursing Officers are within the limit of their cash accountability;
(c) AOs comply with the required number of days within which to liquidate cash advances granted and the necessary supporting documents are attached to the liquidation reports;
(d) the Municipal Accountant (i) checks the completeness of the supporting documents, signatories on liquidation reports; (ii) issues certification that the previous cash advance is liquidated/accounted for before the grant of another cash advance; and (iii) strictly monitors timely submission of liquidation reports and immediate refund of any unused balances and the timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
(e) travelling expenses are given pursuant to EO 77 and lecturers/resource persons are paid in accordance with Budget Circular 2007-1;
(f) submission of an exemption from the Comelec to support the disbursements for donations/assistance/allowance/subsidy granted during election ban;
(g) granting of CAs is limited to disbursements allowed by law and adhere closely to the requirements of the procurement law or RA 9184 and resort to cash advance only on meritorious cases; and
(h) on noted alterations, refund the difference in the amount of the original vis-a-vis the modification on official receipts.

We reiterated our last year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive:
(a) instruct the GSO to process all purchasing concerns and keep track of the movement of stocks on hand from receipt until issuance for accounting, control and accountability purposes;
(b) consider in the budget preparation for the ensuing year, the provision of a storage room so that the procurement of supplies in significant quantities can be stored to lessen the administrative cost in frequent procurements and reimbursements;
(c) instruct the GSO to (i) prepare and maintain stock cards for the purchased supplies; (ii) conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation; and (iii) procure, as far as practicable and feasible, directly from the PS-DBM all anticipated common-use supplies, and resort to local suppliers only upon unavailability of supplies needed; and
(d) require the Municipal Accountant to (i) ensure that all purchase of supplies and materials are recorded under the proper inventory account; (ii) prepare supplies ledger cards for delivered items as called for in the above-quoted regulation.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:
(a) direct the GAD Focal Point Person to coordinate efforts with the Municipal Budget Officer to initiate the preparation of an adjusted GPB to match the available budget for the fund and augment PPAs that had incurred overspending during the year, if warranted;
(b) provide justification on the noted ineligible charges to the fund specified under Item 12.13 of the memorandum;
(c) take note of the ineligible charges to prevent recurrence in the future and utilize in full the total appropriated fund in accordance with the GPB approved by the DILG to ensure full attainment of the GAD targets/objectives;
(d) instruct the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the requirements on the preparation of Subsidiary Ledgers in consonance with COA Circular 2021-008; and
(e) require the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to review the approved GAD Plan and Budget and allow those expenses that are directly related in the implementation of GAD PPAs. Avoid, as much as possible, allowing grants/financial assistance that do not directly address specific gender issues in the locality to be charged under the GAD Fund.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Local Chief Executive, thru the OIC-MENRO:
(a) find a suitable location for the central MRF of the LGU and plan appropriate necessary actions such as inclusion of adequate funding to establish the same, among others;
(b) carry on with the linkage already started with the Barangays of the Municipality in gaining support for the implementation of the ordinance specifically on the establishment of Barangay MRFs by recommending the clustering thereof as allowed by the Act and provide technical assistance on its establishment, if warranted;
(c) intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay, following the strategies identified under the approved 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU and with focus on the volume reduction at source in cognizance with pertinent section as cited above;
(d) exercise strong political will to implement the applicable ordinances pertaining to Solid Waste Management.

